Here is a simple implementation of a queue using two stacks in Java:

```java
import java.util.EmptyStackException;
import java.util.Stack;

public class QueueUsingStacks {
    private Stack<Integer> stack1 = new Stack<>();
    private Stack<Integer> stack2 = new Stack<>();

    // Add element to the queue
    public void enqueue(int value) {
        stack1.push(value);
    }

    // Remove and return the head of the queue
    public int dequeue() {
        if (stack2.isEmpty()) {
            while (!stack1.isEmpty()) {
                stack2.push(stack1.pop());
            }
        }

        if (stack2.isEmpty()) {
            throw new EmptyStackException();
        }

        return stack2.pop();
    }

    // Check if the queue is empty
    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return stack1.isEmpty() && stack2.isEmpty();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        QueueUsingStacks queue = new QueueUsingStacks();

        queue.enqueue(1);
        queue.enqueue(2);
        queue.enqueue(3);

        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 1
        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 2

        queue.enqueue(4);

        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 3
        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 4
    }
}
```

In this code, we use `stack1` to hold the elements that are added to the queue (the "back" of the queue), and `stack2` to hold the elements that will be removed next (the "front" of the queue).

When an element is added to the queue with `enqueue`, it's simply pushed onto `stack1`. When an element is removed from the queue with `dequeue`, if `stack2` is empty, we pop all the elements from `stack1` and push them onto `stack2`, effectively reversing the order. Then we pop and return the top element from `stack2`.

This way, even though we're using two stacks, the overall behavior of the class is that of a queue.

Here is a simple C++ program to check if two strings are anagrams of each other. An anagram is a word or phrase formed by rearranging the letters of a different word or phrase, typically using all the original letters exactly once.

