        return stack2.pop();
    }

    // Check if the queue is empty
    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return stack1.isEmpty() && stack2.isEmpty();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        QueueUsingStacks queue = new QueueUsingStacks();

        queue.enqueue(1);
        queue.enqueue(2);
        queue.enqueue(3);

        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 1
        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 2

        queue.enqueue(4);

        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 3
    }
}
```

In this code, we use `stack1` to hold the elements that are added to the queue (this corresponds to the rear of the queue). When a user calls `dequeue()`, if `stack2` is empty, we pop all elements from `stack1` and push them onto `stack2`. This way, when we finally call `stack2.pop()`, it removes the element that was originally added first (the front of the queue).

Please note that this solution is not the most efficient one because it requires additional operations when shifting elements from `stack1` to `stack2`. However, it clearly demonstrates how to implement a queue using two stacks.

