Here is a simple implementation of a queue using two stacks in Java:

```java
import java.util.EmptyStackException;
import java.util.Stack;

public class QueueUsingStacks {
    private Stack<Integer> stack1 = new Stack<>();
    private Stack<Integer> stack2 = new Stack<>();

    // Add element to the queue
    public void enqueue(int value) {
        stack1.push(value);
    }

    // Remove and return element from the queue
    public int dequeue() {
        if (stack2.isEmpty()) {
            while (!stack1.isEmpty()) {
                stack2.push(stack1.pop());
            }
        }

        if (stack2.isEmpty()) {
            throw new EmptyStackException();
        }

        return stack2.pop();
    }

    // Check if the queue is empty
    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return stack1.isEmpty() && stack2.isEmpty();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        QueueUsingStacks queue = new QueueUsingStacks();

        queue.enqueue(1);
        queue.enqueue(2);
        queue.enqueue(3);

        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 1
        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 2

        queue.enqueue(4);

        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 3
        System.out.println(queue.dequeue()); // prints 4
    }
}
```

In this code, we use `stack1` to hold the elements that are added to the queue (`enqueue` operation). When a user calls `dequeue`, if `stack2` is empty, we pop all elements from `stack1` and push them onto `stack2`. This way, the order of the elements is preserved: the first element added to the queue will be the last one popped from `stack1`, and thus the first one pushed onto `stack2`, and therefore the first one to be popped from `stack2`.

Please note that this implementation adds some overhead because it needs to transfer elements from one stack to another when `dequeue` is called and `stack2` is empty. However, it maintains the FIFO (first-in, first-out) principle of a queue.

Here is a simple C++ program that checks if two strings are anagrams of each other:

