Here is a simple implementation of a queue using two stacks in Java:

```java
import java.util.EmptyStackException;
import java.util.Stack;

public class QueueUsingStacks {
    private Stack<Integer> stackNewestElements = new Stack<Integer>();
    private Stack<Integer> stackOldestElements = new Stack<Integer>();

    // This method enqueues an element into the queue. 
    public void enqueue(int value) {
        stackNewestElements.push(value);
    }

    // This method dequeues an element from the queue. 
    public int dequeue() {
        if (stackOldestElements.isEmpty()) {
            while (!stackNewestElements.isEmpty()) {
                stackOldestElements.push(stackNewestElements.pop());
            }
        }

        if (stackOldestElements.isEmpty()) {
            throw new EmptyStackException();
        }

        return stackOldestElements.pop();
    }

    // This method checks if the queue is empty.
    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return stackNewestElements.isEmpty() && stackOldestElements.isEmpty();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        QueueUsingStacks queue = new QueueUsingStacks();

        queue.enqueue(10);
        queue.enqueue(20);

        System.out.println("Dequeued: " + queue.dequeue());

        queue.enqueue(30);

        System.out.println("Dequeued: " + queue.dequeue());
        System.out.println("Dequeued: " + queue.dequeue());
    }
}
```

In this code, we use `stackNewestElements` to hold the newest elements in the queue, and `stackOldestElements` to hold the oldest elements. When an element is enqueued, it's added to `stackNewestElements`. When an element is dequeued, if `stackOldestElements` is empty, we transfer all elements from `stackNewestElements` to `stackOldestElements`. This way, the first element that was pushed onto `stackNewestElements` will be the first one popped from `stackOldestElements`.

Please note that this is a very basic implementation for educational purposes. In a real-world application, you'd want to consider synchronization, error handling, and possibly other improvements depending on the specific requirements.

Here is a simple C++ program to check if two strings are anagram of each other. Two strings are said to be anagrams if they contain same characters but possibly in different order.

```cpp
#include<iostream>
#include<string>
#include<algorithm>

bool areAnagram(string str1, string str2) {
    // If both strings are not of equal length then they can't be anagram
    if (str1.length() != str2.length()) {
        return false;
    }

    sort(str1.begin(), str1.end());
    sort(str2.begin(), str2.end());

    // Compare sorted strings
    for (int i = 0; i < str1.length(); i++)
        if (str1[i] != str2[i])
            return false;

    return true;
}

int main() {
    string str1 = "listen";
    string str2 = "silent";

    if(areAnagram(str1, str2))
        cout << str1 << " and " << str2 << " are anagrams";
    else
        cout << str1 << " and " << str2 << " are not anagrams";

    return 0;
}
```

