Here is a simple implementation of a min heap in C++ using an array to store the elements:

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

class MinHeap {
private:
    std::vector<int> heap;

    void siftDown(int index) {
        int smallest = index;
        int leftChild = 2 * index + 1;
        int rightChild = 2 * index + 2;

        if (leftChild < heap.size() && heap[leftChild] < heap[smallest]) {
            smallest = leftChild;
        }

        if (rightChild < heap.size() && heap[rightChild] < heap[smallest]) {
            smallest = rightChild;
        }

        if (smallest != index) {
            std::swap(heap[index], heap[smallest]);
            siftDown(smallest);
        }
    }

public:
    MinHeap() {}

    void push(int value) {
        heap.push_back(value);
        siftUp(heap.size() - 1);
    }

    int top() const {
        return heap.front();
    }

    void pop() {
        heap.front() = heap.back();
        heap.pop_back();
        siftDown(0);
    }

    bool empty() const {
        return heap.empty();
    }

private:
    void siftUp(int index) {
        while (index > 0 && heap[(index - 1) / 2] > heap[index]) {
            std::swap(heap[(index - 1) / 2], heap[index]);
            index = (index - 1) / 2;
        }
    }
};
```

This implementation uses a `std::vector` to store the elements of the heap. The `push`, `top`, `pop`, and `empty` functions provide the basic interface for a min heap.

The `siftDown` function is used to maintain the heap property after an element is removed from the top of the heap. The `siftUp` function is used to maintain the heap property after an element is added to the heap.

Note that this implementation assumes that the elements of the heap can be compared using the `<` operator. If you need to use a different comparison function, you can modify the `siftDown` and `siftUp` functions accordingly.

Here's a Java program to check if a binary tree is balanced. This program uses the concept of calculating the height of the left and right subtrees for each node and comparing their difference. If the difference is more than 1, it means the tree is not balanced at that node.

